@@dHISTORY@@W

When the Ninth Meridian Rite failed and the charter road system collapsed, the
legitimate caravan economy fragmented into reaver strongholds, cult toll courts,
and abandoned cistern vaults. In that breakdown a different kind of operator
flourished: those who moved through institutional seams, traded in what
registries could not see, and survived by knowing which doors had been bricked
over and which still opened from the inside. The cipher tradition crystallized
among these figures — route guides who sold rival convoy routes, fence operators
managing contraband between the Saltglass Reach and the Five Cities, private
intelligence dealers who made the post-collapse road network navigable for those
who could pay. The current generation inherits a craft older than any guild,
built on the principle that every system of control creates its own perimeter,
and every perimeter has a gap.

@@dCIPHER@@W

Ciphers are opportunists of motion and timing, winning through angles,
misdirection, and surgical violence. They strike where armor and awareness are
weakest.

